{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-8e113acd20a2ef5a", "type": "tool_result", "content": "=== 2605.11739 ===\n# Learning to Foresee: Unveiling the Unlocking Efficiency of On-Policy Distillation\narXiv: 2605.11739\nAuthors: Yuchen Cai, Ding Cao, Liang Lin, Chunxi Luo, Xin Xu, Kai Yang, Weijie Liu, Saiyong Yang, Tianxiang Zhao, Guangzhong Sun, Guiquan Liu, Junfeng Fang\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: \nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. The paper identifies that On-Policy Distillation (OPD) achieves efficiency through a \"foresight\" mechanism, establishing a stable update trajectory toward the final model early in training.\n  2. OPD exhibits Functional Redundancy Avoidance by concentrating parameter updates on high-marginal-utility modules while suppressing changes in low-utility regions like peripheral layers.\n  3. OPD demonstrates Early Low-Rank Lock-in by stabilizing its dominant update subspaces early in training, which align closely with the final update subspace.\n  4. A checkpoint at only 10% of OPD training progress recovers approximately 80% of the final reasoning performance after module-wise norm scaling.\n  5. The paper proposes EffOPD, a plug-and-play acceleration method that speeds up OPD by performing linear extrapolation along the early stabilized update directions.\n  6. EffOPD adaptively selects an extrapolation step size using lightweight validation feedback to prevent performance degradation from excessive extrapolation.\n  7. EffOPD achieves an average training acceleration of 3× over multiple baselines across model scales from 1.5B to 32B parameters while maintaining comparable final performance.\n=== 2605.08063 ===\n# Flow-OPD: On-Policy Distillation for Flow Matching Models\narXiv: 2605.08063\nAuthors: Zhen Fang, Wenxuan Huang, Yu Zeng, Yiming Zhao, Shuang Chen, Kaituo Feng, Yunlong Lin, Lin Chen, Zehui Chen, Shaosheng Cao, Feng Zhao\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: \nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We provide an empirical analysis of multi-task GRPO failure modes in Flow Matching models, identifying reward sparsity and gradient interference, and introduce the On-Policy Distillation paradigm to their post-training for the first time.\n  2. We propose Flow-OPD, a two-stage post-training framework that decouples expertise acquisition from model unification via a Flow-based Cold-Start strategy, task routing dense labeling, and Manifold Anchor Regularization.\n  3. We demonstrate that Flow-OPD achieves a substantial 10-point average improvement over the GRPO baseline, enables the unified student to surpass specialized teachers, and exhibits exceptional out-of-distribution generalization capabilities.\n=== 2602.02994 ===\n# Video-OPD: Efficient Post-Training of Multimodal Large Language Models for Temporal Video Grounding via On-Policy Distillation\narXiv: 2602.02994\nAuthors: \nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: \nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We identify sparse rewards and high computational overhead from multi-rollout training as key limitations of GRPO-based post-training for TVG.\n  2. We propose Video-OPD, a post-training framework that uses dense token-level supervision from a teacher via reverse KL divergence to improve credit assignment and convergence.\n  3. We introduce TVDF, a curriculum that validates teacher reliability with ground-truth annotations and prioritizes high teacher-student disagreement trajectories for efficient training.\n  4. Extensive experiments confirm Video-OPD outperforms GRPO on TVG and video understanding benchmarks with faster convergence and lower computational cost.\n\nTags: experiments, we identify, we propose, we introduce\n=== 2606.07082 ===\n# On the Geometry of On-Policy Distillation\narXiv: 2606.07082\nAuthors: Zhennan Shen, Yanshu Li, Qingyu Yin, Chak Tou Leong, Zhilin Wang, Yanxu Chen, Rongduo Han, Sunbowen Lee, Yi R. Fung\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: \nStatus: unread\n=== 2605.13724 ===\n# AnyFlow: Any-Step Video Diffusion Model with On-Policy Flow Map Distillation\narXiv: 2605.13724\nAuthors: Yuchao Gu, Guian Fang, Yuxin Jiang, Weijia Mao, Song Han, Han Cai, Mike Zheng Shou\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: \nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of AnyFlow, the first any-step video diffusion distillation framework built on flow maps, enabling a single model to support arbitrary inference budgets.\n  2. Proposal of flow map backward simulation for on-policy flow map distillation to mitigate test-time errors through efficient trajectory decomposition.\n  3. Validation of AnyFlow across architectures and model scales, establishing it as a scalable solution for high-quality, any-step video generation.\n=== 2605.21851 ===\n# OPPO: Bayesian Value Recursion for Token-Level Credit Assignment in LLM Reasoning\narXiv: 2605.21851\nAuthors: Yu Li, Rui Miao, Tian Lan, Zhengling Qi\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: \nStatus: unread\n=== 2606.06021 ===\n# OPRD: On-Policy Representation Distillation\narXiv: 2606.06021\nAuthors: Shenzhi Yang, Guangcheng Zhu, Bowen Song, Haobo Wang, Mingxuan Xia, Xing Zheng, Yingfan Ma, Zhongqi Chen, Weiqiang Wang, Gang Chen\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: \nStatus: unread", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "b463d47f-cd58-4dc5-a65b-ef7e897499eb", "uuid": "2eb102ce-b62b-43b4-8c35-7d2f063745c8", "timestamp": "2026-07-24T08:15:21.459Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "=== 2605.11739 ===\n# Learning to Foresee: Unveiling the Unlocking Efficiency of On-Policy Distillation\narXiv: 2605.11739\nAuthors: Yuchen Cai, Ding Cao, Liang Lin, Chunxi Luo, Xin Xu, Kai Yang, Weijie Liu, Saiyong Yang, Tianxiang Zhao, Guangzhong Sun, Guiquan Liu, Junfeng Fang\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: \nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. The paper identifies that On-Policy Distillation (OPD) achieves efficiency through a \"foresight\" mechanism, establishing a stable update trajectory toward the final model early in training.\n  2. OPD exhibits Functional Redundancy Avoidance by concentrating parameter updates on high-marginal-utility modules while suppressing changes in low-utility regions like peripheral layers.\n  3. OPD demonstrates Early Low-Rank Lock-in by stabilizing its dominant update subspaces early in training, which align closely with the final update subspace.\n  4. A checkpoint at only 10% of OPD training progress recovers approximately 80% of the final reasoning performance after module-wise norm scaling.\n  5. The paper proposes EffOPD, a plug-and-play acceleration method that speeds up OPD by performing linear extrapolation along the early stabilized update directions.\n  6. EffOPD adaptively selects an extrapolation step size using lightweight validation feedback to prevent performance degradation from excessive extrapolation.\n  7. EffOPD achieves an average training acceleration of 3× over multiple baselines across model scales from 1.5B to 32B parameters while maintaining comparable final performance.\n=== 2605.08063 ===\n# Flow-OPD: On-Policy Distillation for Flow Matching Models\narXiv: 2605.08063\nAuthors: Zhen Fang, Wenxuan Huang, Yu Zeng, Yiming Zhao, Shuang Chen, Kaituo Feng, Yunlong Lin, Lin Chen, Zehui Chen, Shaosheng Cao, Feng Zhao\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: \nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We provide an empirical analysis of multi-task GRPO failure modes in Flow Matching models, identifying reward sparsity and gradient interference, and introduce the On-Policy Distillation paradigm to their post-training for the first time.\n  2. We propose Flow-OPD, a two-stage post-training framework that decouples expertise acquisition from model unification via a Flow-based Cold-Start strategy, task routing dense labeling, and Manifold Anchor Regularization.\n  3. We demonstrate that Flow-OPD achieves a substantial 10-point average improvement over the GRPO baseline, enables the unified student to surpass specialized teachers, and exhibits exceptional out-of-distribution generalization capabilities.\n=== 2602.02994 ===\n# Video-OPD: Efficient Post-Training of Multimodal Large Language Models for Temporal Video Grounding via On-Policy Distillation\narXiv: 2602.02994\nAuthors: \nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: \nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We identify sparse rewards and high computational overhead from multi-rollout training as key limitations of GRPO-based post-training for TVG.\n  2. We propose Video-OPD, a post-training framework that uses dense token-level supervision from a teacher via reverse KL divergence to improve credit assignment and convergence.\n  3. We introduce TVDF, a curriculum that validates teacher reliability with ground-truth annotations and prioritizes high teacher-student disagreement trajectories for efficient training.\n  4. Extensive experiments confirm Video-OPD outperforms GRPO on TVG and video understanding benchmarks with faster convergence and lower computational cost.\n\nTags: experiments, we identify, we propose, we introduce\n=== 2606.07082 ===\n# On the Geometry of On-Policy Distillation\narXiv: 2606.07082\nAuthors: Zhennan Shen, Yanshu Li, Qingyu Yin, Chak Tou Leong, Zhilin Wang, Yanxu Chen, Rongduo Han, Sunbowen Lee, Yi R. Fung\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: \nStatus: unread\n=== 2605.13724 ===\n# AnyFlow: Any-Step Video Diffusion Model with On-Policy Flow Map Distillation\narXiv: 2605.13724\nAuthors: Yuchao Gu, Guian Fang, Yuxin Jiang, Weijia Mao, Song Han, Han Cai, Mike Zheng Shou\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: \nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of AnyFlow, the first any-step video diffusion distillation framework built on flow maps, enabling a single model to support arbitrary inference budgets.\n  2. Proposal of flow map backward simulation for on-policy flow map distillation to mitigate test-time errors through efficient trajectory decomposition.\n  3. Validation of AnyFlow across architectures and model scales, establishing it as a scalable solution for high-quality